<section id="components">
  <h2>Core Components Explained</h2>
  <p class="section-lead">Each component serves a distinct role in the compound AI pipeline.</p>

  <div class="cards">
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-icon" style="background:rgba(108,92,231,0.15);">🧠</div>
      <h3>The Planner</h3>
      <p>A high-reasoning LLM (Devin-Planner) that takes a natural language prompt and decomposes it into a step-by-step strategy — file architecture, tool selection, estimated timelines. In Devin 2.0, this became "Interactive Planning" where users can modify the plan before execution begins.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-icon" style="background:rgba(0,206,201,0.15);">⌨️</div>
      <h3>The Coder</h3>
      <p>A code-specialized model trained on high-quality code tokens. Handles multi-language generation, context-aware editing across files, and pattern replication from existing codebases. Works closely with the editor tool in the Devbox.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-icon" style="background:rgba(253,121,168,0.15);">🔍</div>
      <h3>The Critic</h3>
      <p>An adversarial review model that inspects generated code for security vulnerabilities, logic errors, and style violations before anything is committed. Feeds confidence scores back to the orchestrator — low confidence triggers a "clarification request" to the human.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-icon" style="background:rgba(253,203,110,0.15);">🌐</div>
      <h3>The Browser Agent</h3>
      <p>An agent designed to navigate the web, scrape documentation, look up Stack Overflow / official docs, and synthesize information. Lets Devin learn new libraries at runtime rather than relying solely on training data.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-icon" style="background:rgba(0,184,148,0.15);">🔄</div>
      <h3>The Orchestrator</h3>
      <p>Coordinates the swarm. Dispatches subtasks to the right specialist model, manages session state, routes outputs between Planner → Coder → Critic loops, and handles multi-agent parallel execution in Devin 2.0.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-icon" style="background:rgba(108,92,231,0.15);">📦</div>
      <h3>The Devbox (Sandbox)</h3>
      <p>A secure, isolated VM per session with a shell, code editor, and browser. This is where code actually runs. Cannot access production databases unless credentials are explicitly provided. Enterprise deployments can run the Devbox in customer VPCs via AWS PrivateLink.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h4>Deployment Models</h4>
  <div class="cards" style="grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(240px, 1fr));">
    <div class="card">
      <h3>Enterprise SaaS</h3>
      <p>Both Brain + Devbox in Cognition's cloud. Multi-tenant, encrypted at rest and in transit. Each session is isolated.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h3>Customer Dedicated SaaS</h3>
      <p>Single-tenant VPC. Devbox runs in a customer-isolated environment. Connected via AWS PrivateLink or IPSec tunnel.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h3>Customer VPC</h3>
      <p>Devbox runs inside your own VPC (AWS / Azure). Brain still calls Cognition's cloud. Maximum data residency control.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ─── E2E FLOW ─── -->
<section id="flow">
  <h2>End-to-End Flow</h2>
  <p class="section-lead">What happens from the moment you type a prompt to a merged PR.</p>

  <div class="flow-steps">
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-num">STEP 01</div>
      <h3>Task Input</h3>
      <p>User gives Devin a natural language instruction — via the web UI, Slack (@Devin), or an IDE extension. Example: "Build a task management API using FastAPI + PostgreSQL with CRUD endpoints and auth."</p>
    </div>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-num">STEP 02</div>
      <h3>Interactive Planning</h3>
      <p>The <strong>Planner</strong> model researches the codebase (via the Repo Index), develops a detailed plan with steps, files, tools, and architecture. User reviews, modifies, or approves the plan before execution begins.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-num">STEP 03</div>
      <h3>Environment Setup</h3>
      <p>A fresh <strong>Devbox</strong> sandbox spins up. Devin clones the repo, installs dependencies, sets up the dev environment — just like a human would <code>git clone && npm install</code>.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-num">STEP 04</div>
      <h3>Code Generation</h3>
      <p>The <strong>Coder</strong> model writes code file-by-file, following the approved plan. Replicates patterns from the existing codebase. The <strong>Browser Agent</strong> looks up docs for unfamiliar libraries in real time.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-num">STEP 05</div>
      <h3>Test & Debug Loop</h3>
      <p>Devin runs the code, executes tests, reads error outputs. If tests fail, it enters a debug loop — reading stack traces, modifying code, re-running. This loop can iterate dozens of times autonomously.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-num">STEP 06</div>
      <h3>Adversarial Review</h3>
      <p>The <strong>Critic</strong> model reviews the final code for security vulnerabilities, logic errors, and adherence to the plan. Generates a confidence score. Low confidence → asks the human for clarification.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-num">STEP 07</div>
      <h3>PR Submission</h3>
      <p>Devin creates a branch, commits the changes with meaningful messages, and opens a Pull Request on GitHub/GitLab. Includes descriptions, test results, and technical documentation.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-num">STEP 08</div>
      <h3>Post-PR Feedback Loop</h3>
      <p>Devin monitors CI status. If tests break, it auto-fixes. It also responds to reviewer comments on the PR — adjusting code based on human feedback without being re-prompted.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

