<!-- ─── TRADE-OFFS ─── -->
<section id="tradeoffs">
  <h2>Trade-offs & Design Decisions</h2>

  <div class="cards" style="grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;">
    <div class="card">
      <h3>🟢 Autonomy vs Control</h3>
      <p><strong>Devin</strong> maximizes autonomy — great for throughput but you lose visibility into moment-by-moment decisions. <strong>Claude Code</strong> keeps you in the driver's seat — more control but requires your attention. The right choice depends on whether your bottleneck is engineer time or engineer throughput.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h3>🟡 Multi-Model vs Single-Model</h3>
      <p>Devin's compound architecture lets it specialize — the Critic catches what the Coder misses. But it adds latency, coordination overhead, and makes the system harder to debug when things go wrong. Claude's single-model approach is simpler, more predictable, and easier to reason about.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h3>🔵 Cloud Sandbox vs Local</h3>
      <p>Cloud execution means Devin can't mess up your local environment — great for safety. But it means network latency, no access to local tools/VPNs without explicit setup, and a dependency on Cognition's infrastructure. Claude Code runs where your code lives.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h3>🟣 Async vs Sync Workflows</h3>
      <p>Devin's fire-and-forget model scales to dozens of parallel tasks. Claude Code's synchronous model is better when the task needs iteration and judgment. The best teams create clear decision boundaries: "Is this a Devin task or a Claude task?"</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ─── GOTCHAS ─── -->
<section id="gotchas">
  <h2>Gotchas & Caveats</h2>

  <div class="callout callout-danger">
    <div class="callout-title">⚠️ Devin-Specific Gotchas</div>
    <p><strong>Over-eagerness:</strong> Devin sometimes starts committing code and opening PRs before you've approved the approach. Set guardrails in your prompt: "Do not open a PR until I confirm."</p>
    <p style="margin-top:0.7rem"><strong>Ambiguity is the enemy:</strong> Devin struggles with vague requirements. It needs specific component structures, color codes, spacing values. If outcomes aren't straightforwardly verifiable, human review is necessary.</p>
    <p style="margin-top:0.7rem"><strong>SWE-bench reality check:</strong> The official 13.86% resolution rate means most complex, end-to-end tasks are not completed or only partially finished. Independent testing shows 15–30% success in practice.</p>
    <p style="margin-top:0.7rem"><strong>Cost unpredictability:</strong> ACU-based billing ($2.25 per ~15 min) makes costs hard to forecast for complex tasks. A task that takes many debug loops can burn through ACUs quickly.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="callout callout-warn">
    <div class="callout-title">⚠️ Claude Code Gotchas</div>
    <p><strong>Rate limits as the product:</strong> Even at the $200/month Max plan, heavy users hit throttling. One developer noted: "The rate limits are the product. The model is just bait."</p>
    <p style="margin-top:0.7rem"><strong>No free tier:</strong> Every competitor except Devin offers a free path. Claude Code has no free option.</p>
    <p style="margin-top:0.7rem"><strong>Context window limits:</strong> Even with 200K+ tokens, very large codebases require careful chunking.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="callout callout-warn">
    <div class="callout-title">⚠️ General Agent Gotchas</div>
    <p><strong>Benchmark ≠ Production:</strong> Agent scaffolding matters as much as the model. Three frameworks running the same model scored 17 issues apart on 731 problems in the same test.</p>
    <p style="margin-top:0.7rem"><strong>Security:</strong> Any agent with filesystem/CLI access introduces risk. Claude Code had reported RCE vulnerabilities in 2025. Devin's sandbox helps, but credentials leakage is still a human error risk.</p>
    <p style="margin-top:0.7rem"><strong>The "junior-senior paradox":</strong> Devin is senior-level at codebase understanding but junior at execution. This mismatch means it can describe a perfect architecture but stumble implementing it.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ─── WHEN TO USE ─── -->
<section id="when">
  <h2>When to Use What</h2>

  <div class="callout callout-success">
    <div class="callout-title">✅ Use Devin When</div>
    <p>You have a backlog of well-defined, repeatable tickets (bug fixes, security vuln patching, migrations like Angular → React or .NET Framework → .NET Core). When tasks have clear inputs/outputs and can be verified programmatically. When you want to parallelize — spin up a fleet of Devins to execute on every repo simultaneously. When the task would take a junior engineer 4–8 hours.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="callout callout-success">
    <div class="callout-title">✅ Use Claude / Claude Code When</div>
    <p>You need deep reasoning over a complex codebase. Architecture reviews, refactoring decisions where context matters more than speed. When you want interactive, iterative collaboration — "help me understand this problem" not "do this task." When working on novel, ambiguous problems that need human judgment at each step. When you want to stay local and IDE-native.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="callout callout-info">
    <div class="callout-title">🔗 Combine Them</div>
    <p>Use <strong>Claude</strong> to break down a complex feature into smaller, well-scoped tasks. Then assign each task to <strong>Devin</strong> for parallel execution. Connect both to your CI pipeline, linters, and static analysis. Keep human review as the final gate.</p>
  </div>
</section>

